<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#D5E6E1"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#000080" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">clarrissa</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Im a newly 39th season cleric asking for advice.  Up till now Ive mainly been a healer but as mobs get harder, Im doing more crowd control.  What do you use as guage of when to switch from healer to crowd control/rooter?   I have had about 50/50 results of getting it right.<P>Any advice would be appreciated!  =)</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Serina Moonprism Elay</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Most of the time when I was raiding from level 50-60 haveing an ench around was a must. So they were the crowd control I never was. </FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Dystopya</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Around your level you should start to find that having a chanter working in tandem with you is almost a must, and you probably wont be joining groups that wont leave a spot open for a chanter, or forming groups without saving a spot for one.<P>Having a little experience in getting taunt and pulling mobs away from the group to root is good to be able to have every now and then, but its not always feasible in dungeons and high level zones. Nothing is better crowd control than a good mez 8)</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Phalia</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Practice and learn!  Even with an enchanter I sometimes do a little crowd control..root or stun the mob so the chanter can get mez off.  Back in the day tho..If your puller announces 2 mobs, try to root on a little distance away from your party, as it is being pulled.  (Not too far out though since you wont want any more adds).  If you get 3+, root one on the inc, and try to stagger the others away from your party.  Tell your party to back off if they are too close and still getting swung at.  Like I said, it takes practice, and sometimes just getting your party to listen to you is the worst part of it <IMG SRC="http://eqcleric.gameglow.com/ubb/smile.gif"><P>------------------<BR><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=14272" TARGET=_blank>Phalia Kordain</A><BR>57th Templar<BR>Lords of Belterra<BR>Xegony</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Kodachi Darkbane</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Bah you enchanteraholics!  Grab a BARD!  Any good 53+ bard does CC as well as an enchanter as long as the mobs are 55 and lower.  I love my bard  <IMG SRC="http://eqcleric.gameglow.com/ubb/smile.gif">.<P>Kodachi</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Josiefuz</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">One root spell can often save 4+ heal spells.  When it's mana efficient, do it.  Also, when the chanter clearly isn't getting things under control, that's when you step in to help.<P>-Fuz<BR>59 Templar, Sol Ro<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Cali</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">hhmmm<P>At 39 I was leveling with an enc fast.  BUT to share what I knew then and what I have learned since then.<P>Enchanterless crowd control can be best done at those levels with Root.<P>Keep Stun and Root mem'd at all times.  (I like the lowest level ones as they are fastest casting and less resisted.) <P>Look for groupmates like shaman or bards when enchanters are scarce.  40ish should be the time that shaman are talented at slowing to gain agro, moving away from the group, sitting to pull the mob to them, and rooting.  <P>Any class that can cast root can crowd control to a degree.  Paladins are talented at this when they stun to gain agro, then move and root.  Rangers are ok at this but usually to crunchy to be mana effective for the cleric.<P>At 39 with your new CH, crowd control will be falling to others more and more.  Though if you keep stun and root mem'd you should be able to switch on the fly and return to healing quickly.<P>I have learned to very quickly hit my F# key and then my /assist hotkey and stun, root, /assist (orF#) and heal.  <P>As you level up that skill will be more ane more usefull when you do multi group romps.  Assisting the mob to get the target and landing a quick heal then assisting again and again to keep bouncing heals to those in need, who may not be in your group.<P>You should be able to safely keep up 4 heals, 1 stun, 1 root and 2 divines mem'd to handle most group situations.  When buffing needs to happen unmem the lowest heal to swap in buffs quickly.  <P>Good luck!<P>------------------<BR><B>~Calimayrn Anam'Cara</B><BR>Templar of Tunare<BR><B>~Calizana Rhinelander</B><BR>Floating Barbarian Champion<BR>Farstorm ~ Veeshan</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Boanerges</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Sometimes crowd control isn't necessary. I've used a shaman in place of a chanter and 3 slowed mobs is as managable as 1 unslowed.<P>Root has diminishing ability to do crowd control and the upgrades really aren't upgrades.<P>A good puller can also negate the need for crowd control.<P>------------------<BR>Boanerges Thundercry<BR>High Priest of Prexus<BR><A HREF="http://www.cohort.cc" TARGET=_blank>Cohort Chalybeius</A><BR>Cazic Thule Server</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">clarrissa</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Thank you all for your answers!!  This board has been the best 'mentor' for me yet =)<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Jerycho</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I do a lot of duo'ing with monks and warriors. I've found that the rewards are much higher but the challenge is much greater.<P>Root and stun are necessary tools for this to work right.<P>If you are a high elven cleric of Tunare, get yourself the warden symbol -- that mana free root makes CC much easier! <P>Here's the plan - you go into a dungeon with a competent puller/meleer. An SK or monk is best. You find a camp spot and set up. Clear the room pops and start a timer. Use a stopwatch with multiple counters to set a timer for EVERY SINGLE ROOM POP. Learn the times of hte spawn. It is vital that you know this as you need to plan your mana use accordingly.<P>Have your puller go pull singles and doubles. Use stun on the pull in to get aggro from the extras and to stop them. Let hte puller keep coming with the mob that is still moving and start casting root to park the mob that you've stunned.<P>Now, check your timers and mana. If you are going to have room pops consider your mana pool - you want to only be dealing with at most 2 root parks at a time (I've lived through having 5 before - but it wasn't pretty and we where damn lucky!).<P>Basically, I allocate half my mana to healing and half to crowd control, damage dealing. The key is to make sure that you have the mana for what you need to be doing. This means that you have to make calls on nuking the crap out of something so that you can deal with parking the extra mobs that may be popping in the room. Thus leaving you with little mana for heals. <P>Make sure that your partner is well aware of mana and mob situations. If you have a monk make sure htat you communicate on their mend skill - when it's up, when it's used, how much he can do, etc.<P>Be prepared to root the mob he's on if he needs to FD a bit to gain time to mend if you are too low to on mana to heal.<P>Doing CC/healer with a partner is GREAT fun.<P>If you are not in a dungeon, or you don't have a camp with regular spawns, you just need to do 'best judgement.' Try to think of your mana in two piles: one for cc and one for healing. You borrow from one to use the other at a very high interest rate so try to avoid it!</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Helamor</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">In addition to the foregoing, I'd say find a competent paladin.  But at your level a paladin root lasts only 30 seconds if you're lucky, so they're not the best on crowd control.  However, they can take a hit better than a cleric and having a paladin drop out of a hairy combat to root-park and mess around with a MOB is better in my opinion than a cleric dropping out of a combat, getting beaten on, and missing heals.<P>Later on, though, paladins can make decent ghetto mezzers.  My paladin can keep 2 adds under control while being conscripted (i.e. the MOB likes me better than the warrior) as MT on a third MOB with no great difficulty.  With 3 adds and fighting the 4th MOB, it gets a bit dicey.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Serenya</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Even with a chanter I've found that stunning and rooting often comes into play for CC.  I started playing a wee bit with that new stun aoe from Luclin w/my 39 cleric.  I would suggest practicing with that a bit -- it does damage, so less useful with a chanter, but you can use it to stun everything near your melee (it's targeted, so target your main tank and stay out of range) and then start rooting.  Obviously, that will work better if there is someone else in your group who can root as well (there's a wizzie in mine) as you'll get it done faster and more effectively.  </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
</FONT>
